enneth Galbraith presents a compelling and accessible history of economic ideas, from Aristotle through the twentieth century. Examining theories of the past that have a continuing modern resonance, he shows that economics is not a timeless, objective science, but is continually evolving as it is shaped by specific times and places. From Adam Smith's theories during the Industrial Revolution to those of John Maynard Keynes after the Great Depression, Galbraith demonstrates that if economic ideas are to remain relevant, they must continually adapt to the world they inhabit. A lively examination of economic thought in historical context, Economics in Perspective shows how the field has evolved across the centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomic history. 0aEconomicsxHistory. 0aEconomics; History. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh  aA Treatise on Money.  aAdam Müller.  aAdam Smith.  aAlfred Marshall.  aAlvin Harvey Hansen.  aAristotle.  aArthur C. Pigou.  aAuguste Walras.  aBritain.  aChristianity.  aDavid Ricardo.  aFrance.  aFranklin D. Roosevelt.  aFriedrich Engels.  aGeorg Friedrich List.  aGermany.  aGreat Depression.  aGreece.  aGreenbacks.  aHarvard University.  aHenry Charles Carey.  aHenry George.  aHerbert Spencer.  aIndustrial Revolution.  aIrving Fisher.  aJean Baptiste Say.  aJean Charles Léonard de Sismondi.  aJeremy Bentham.  aJohn Maynard Keynes.  aJohn R. Commons.  aJohn Stuart Mill.  aJoseph Schumpeter.  aKarl Marx.  aKarl Menger.  aKeynesian Revolution.  aKeynesian economics.  aLauchlin Currie.  aLenin (Vladimir Ilyich Ulyanov).  aMiddle Ages.  aNational Recovery Act.  aNicole Oresme.  aOctober Revolution.  aOtto von Bismarck.  aPhysiocrats.  aPierre Joseph Proudhon.  aPlato.  